			<p>Couples planning a <a href="/weddings">South Asian wedding in Vancouver</a> often come to us with a question they're framing as either/or: "Should we do a chai station or a coffee bar?" Our answer, almost without exception, is: both. After catering hundreds of weddings, we've watched the same pattern unfold every time. Chai serves one part of the celebration. Coffee serves another. And together, they cover every guest, every age group, every moment of the day.</p>

			<h2>Chai is Memory. Coffee is <em>Function.</em></h2>
			<p>Chai is rooted in cultural memory. For South Asian guests, masala chai is the smell of mornings at home, of grandmothers at the stove, of every gathering where a family came together. When you serve chai at a wedding, you're not just serving a drink — you're invoking a feeling.</p>
			<p>Coffee plays a different role. It's functional. It's the drink that keeps the reception going past midnight. It's the espresso that revives Uncle Sanjay before he has to drive back to Surrey. It's the cappuccino that makes the morning-after brunch feel like an indulgence.</p>

			<h2>The Live <em>Chai Bar</em></h2>
			<p>A live chai station is one of the most atmospheric additions to any wedding. We brew masala chai fresh on-site in copper urns, with cardamom, ginger, fennel, and black peppercorns. Guests gather around it. Conversations slow down. The air smells like warmth.</p>
			<p>Best moments to deploy a chai bar:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Pre-ceremony — for early-arriving guests on a chilly Vancouver morning</li>
				<li>Sangeet — pair with chaat stations for an immersive evening</li>
				<li>Ceremony lunch — particularly for vegetarian-heavy menus</li>
				<li>Late-night reception — the moment when everyone needs something warm</li>
				<li>Morning-after brunch — alongside parathas and fresh-baked pastries</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>The Barista <em>Coffee Station</em></h2>
			<p>A specialty coffee bar from <a href="/cafe-catering">Sula Café</a> is a different beast. Single-origin beans, professional baristas, full espresso service — americanos, cortados, lattes, flat whites. We bring plant-based milks, alternative sweeteners, and a small menu of seasonal specialties.</p>
			<p>Best moments for the coffee station:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Reception dessert hour — pairs beautifully with kheer or gulab jamun</li>
				<li>Late-night second wind — the post-dinner energy boost</li>
				<li>Morning-after brunch — for the guests who flew in</li>
				<li>Sunday post-wedding gatherings — quiet, family-only moments</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Why <em>Both</em> Works</h2>
			<p>Different generations gravitate toward different drinks. Different moments of the day call for different rituals. By offering both, you're not making guests choose — you're inviting them to enjoy the celebration in whatever way feels most like home.</p>
			<p>And practically: chai serves the cultural moments. Coffee serves the long ones. A wedding has both.</p>

			<h2>The <em>Pairings</em> That Matter</h2>
			<p>Both chai and coffee shine when paired with the right accompaniments. Some of our favourite combinations:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Masala chai + masala biscuits, koliyada, samosas</li>
				<li>Cardamom chai + cardamom shortbread, fresh croissants</li>
				<li>Espresso + gulab jamun, ras malai</li>
				<li>Cortado + dark chocolate truffles, Indian sweets</li>
				<li>Iced latte + summer wedding receptions, dessert hours</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Logistics That <em>Matter</em></h2>
			<p>If you're considering both, here's what to plan for:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Power access — espresso machines and chai urns both need outlets</li>
				<li>Two separate stations — don't combine them into one cramped corner</li>
				<li>Trained baristas — for coffee, the skill matters as much as the beans</li>
				<li>Branded signage — small touches make stations feel intentional</li>
				<li>Timing — open chai earlier, open coffee later in the evening</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
			<p>A wedding isn't a single event — it's a series of moments. The drinks you serve mark each one. Chai for the warm rituals. Coffee for the long ones. And both, together, for guests of every age and every tradition.</p>
